Using information from a published phylogeny and joining that data one can see that it appears the genus may have orinated in the Ozarks. Dispersal models however suggest instead that the species dispersed to the Ozarks when compared to the location of the last common ancestor. We will explore this contrast in future maps

library(geosphere)


vv= as.data.frame(Espeldf%>%
                    filter(!is.na(decimalLongitude),!is.na(decimalLatitude))%>%
                    select(decimalLongitude,decimalLatitude))



v=data.frame(
  ids = 1:nrow(vv),
  x=vv$decimalLongitude,
  y=vv$decimalLatitude)



D <- distm(vv, vv, fun=distVincentyEllipsoid) 



mat2list <- function(D) {
  n = dim(D)[1]
  k <- 1
  e <- matrix(ncol = 3,nrow = n*(n-1)/2)
  for (i in 1:(n-1)) {
    for (j in (i+1):n) {
      e[k,] = c(i,j,D[i,j])
      k<-k+1
    }
  }
  return(e)
}

eD = mat2list(D/1000)

net <- graph.data.frame(eD[,1:2],directed = FALSE, vertices = v)
E(net)$weight <- eD[,3] # Important use edge weight rather than net$weight
mst <- minimum.spanning.tree(net)

par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(0,1,0.75,0)) 
plot(net,vertex.label=NA)
plot(mst, vertex.shape="none",edge.label=round(E(mst)$weight))

Here we use two packages to create (above) minimal spanning trees of the geographic distribution data and plot it using the path geom of ggplot (below) 

## grourp the distance matrix in to lines for use with ggplot geom_path

mst2lines <- function(mst, vv) {
  me = get.edges(mst,1:ecount(mst))
  R = data.frame(lon=NULL,lat=NULL,group=NULL)
  for (k in 1:ecount(mst)) {
    A = vv[me[k,],]
    A$group = k
    R <- rbind(R,A)
  }
  rownames(R) <- NULL
  return(R)
}

R = mst2lines(mst,vv)
## plot with geom_path and quick map
